larsbrinkhoff on Mar 5, 2024 · edited by larsbrinkhoff
Long before I was involved Ken Harrienstien had ITS running on his emulator, and somewhat later Bob Supnik repeated the feat for his SIMH suite. However, these two emulators "only" support the KS10, which doesn't have the full glory of AI lab hardware.
Huge strides were enabled by @rcornwell adding ITS support to his KA10 emulator. (The emulator was built on Supnik's SIMH framework.) We worked together on this during fall 2017, ultimately booting successfully on January 8, 2018. Much of the following AI lab emulation came out of this.
@philbudne added Type 340 support, which was the start of many additions to support the AI lab hardware. Actually, Chaosnet came before this, but to me it felt like the 340 kicked off something. Later @aap and I added the Knight TV which really added momentum.
@eswenson1 and @atsampson did almost everything related to Maclisp, Macsyma, Muddle, and Zork.
@bictorv is the cherished champion of Chaosnet.
Without the effort of @lisper et al we probably wouldn't have the wealth of backup data to draw from. Without that, ITS would only have been a whisper of a ghost of its former grandeur.
And of course, ITS preservation started already in the 80s with @bawden and many others, most of which are unsung heroes.


